The White House released a report on the national security implications of climate change. President Obama will address the importance of acting on climate change in his commencement speech at the United States Coast Guard Academy. Climate change poses immediate risks to national security, contributing to natural disasters, humanitarian crises, and potential conflicts over resources. The Department of Defense is assessing the vulnerability of military facilities to climate change and studying the implications of increased demand for the National Guard after extreme weather events. The EPA will implement standards to reduce carbon pollution from power plants. The US has increased its use of wind and solar energy and is working with industry to address methane emissions. The goal is to deploy 3 gigawatts of renewable energy on military installations by 2025.